00:15.320 --> 00:26.320
Good afternoon. Welcome to the Johnson Space Center open house. We think we've
exceeded our expectations. We thought we'd have about 20,000 people show up

00:26.320 --> 00:36.540
today just to the open house. We think that we're well over 70,000 now. So... We
thank you.

00:40.660 --> 00:48.140
We certainly thank you for your support. I'm Sue Garman. I'm the Executive
Assistant to the Director of the Johnson Space Center. And on behalf of all the

00:48.140 --> 00:56.240
employees here, we're happy to have you here. We're happy to have all of our
friends and neighbors in. And glad that you support the United States Space

00:56.240 --> 01:03.860
Program. We hope that you have taken advantage and will for the rest of the time
that the Space Center is open today of the unique opportunity to look around and

01:03.860 --> 01:12.300
see the kind of work that we do to help make sure that we have a human
spaceflight program. This last session deals with the historic Apollo 13

01:12.300 --> 01:19.960
mission, and it features four of the flight controllers who successfully brought
the astronauts home. We're going to follow this with a question and answer

01:19.960 --> 01:31.380
session. Let me introduce them in order from my right on across. first is Gene
Kranz. Gene holds a degree in Aeronautical Engineering. Prior to coming to NASA,

01:31.600 --> 01:40.500
he worked as a flight loads test engineer at McDonnell Aircraft. He served as a
pilot in the Air Force, and he worked as a flight test engineer at Holloman Air

01:40.500 --> 01:50.280
Force Base. He joined NASA in 1960 and worked as a flight director in both the
Mercury and Gemini programs. As the flight director for the Apollo and the

01:50.280 --> 01:59.580
Skylab programs, he led the team in mission control during the first lunar
landing and the successful return of the Apollo 13 crew. During the Shuttle Era,

02:00.400 --> 02:21.040
Gene served as the Deputy Director of Flight Operations and the Director of
Mission Operations. He retired from NASA in 1994. Gerry Griffin holds

02:21.040 --> 02:29.420
a degree in Aeronautical Engineering. Prior to coming to NASA, he served as an
officer in the Air Force and he worked as an aerospace engineer with the Douglas

02:29.420 --> 02:38.960
Aircraft Company. He joined NASA in 1964 and he worked as a flight controller
for all of the Gemini flights and as a flight director for all of the 11 Apollo

02:38.960 --> 02:48.920
missions. His positions at NASA included Assistant Administrator for Legislative
Affairs, Deputy Associate Administrator for Manned Space Flight, Deputy Director

02:48.920 --> 02:58.360
of the Dryden Flight Research Center, Associate Administrator for External
Relations, and Deputy Director of the Kennedy Space Center. He also served as a

02:58.360 --> 03:11.600
Director of the Johnson Space Center from 1982 until his retirement from NASA.
Next is

03:11.600 --> 03:21.320
Jerry Bostick. Jerry holds a degree in civil engineering. He joined NASA as an
aerospace engineer at the Langley Space Center in 1962 and he transferred to

03:21.320 --> 03:30.480
Houston in the same year. He worked as a flight controller for the Mercury,
Gemini, Apollo, and Skylab missions. He was the flight dynamics officer for the

03:30.480 --> 03:39.760
Apollo 13 mission. His other positions at NASA included executive assistant to
the NASA administrator, deputy manager of the space shuttle program, and

03:39.760 --> 03:47.980
director of mission support. Since leaving NASA, he has worked as the vice
president of space systems for Grumman Corporation, and is currently the

03:47.980 --> 03:51.780
director of business development for Northrop Grumman Technical Services.

03:57.800 --> 04:09.500
And on my far right is John Aaron. John holds a degree in physics. He joined NASA
in 1964 as a vehicle systems engineer for the Gemini program. John was a flight

04:09.500 --> 04:18.700
controller for the Gemini and Apollo missions. During the Skylab program, he was
the section head for electrical power, sequential, and instrumentation systems.

04:19.020 --> 04:27.900
His other positions at NASA have included management positions working with
spacecraft software, management positions with the space station program, acting

04:27.900 --> 04:35.780
assistant administrator for exploration, and assistant director of engineering
at the Johnson Space Center. He is currently the manager of the systems

04:35.780 --> 04:37.740
engineering office. Let's welcome all of them.

04:46.440 --> 05:01.720
Okay, this is going to be a very informal session up here. We haven't rehearsed
this script. The Apollo 13 I think really had several key points associated with

05:01.720 --> 05:11.080
it. The first thing was I look at it as a real miracle of leadership. We were
fortunate, all of us up here, to grow up under some exemplary leaders. We had

05:11.080 --> 05:24.760
George Miller. We had Jim McDivitt, George Lowe. We had Chris Kraft, Deke
Slayton, Dr. Gilruth. And each of these people gave true meaning to authority

05:24.760 --> 05:34.180
with responsibility. So that when it came time to fly missions, these folks were
with us every step of the way. They gave us the job and they expected us to do

05:34.180 --> 05:43.020
it. And I think that was one of the real keys to the success of that mission and
all the missions that we had in the program. The second element was associated

05:43.020 --> 05:53.340
with the people. The people were universally young, they were convinced that the
impossible was truly possible, they had gone through very rigorous training they

05:53.340 --> 06:02.360
had grown up in the business of mission operations. and we would spend the days,
weeks, months, and eventually the years together not only working in mission

06:02.360 --> 06:13.080
control, but working in our offices, building the game plan, developing
confidence in ourselves, and confidence in each other. The training personnel we

06:13.080 --> 06:21.780
had were the best in the world, because those were the ones that gave us the can
-do attitude, the never surrender, and with that kind of a background, we moved

06:21.780 --> 06:33.200
into the Apollo program. There had been several very key missions in Apollo, and
everyone up here worked those missions. We went to the moon in Apollo 11. We had

06:33.200 --> 06:41.220
difficulties getting down to the surface, but we made it. Apollo 12, we were
struck by lightning, and I believe Jerry was the flight director there, and

06:41.220 --> 06:52.440
you've got another key guy on his right, John Aaron, who made the calls to get
the spacecraft back to life again. Apollo 13 came along, so we were no... The

06:52.440 --> 07:02.360
kinds of problems that we had, we were convinced we could work and lick. So I
think we were ready at 55-55 when the problem occurred on board the spacecraft.

07:02.480 --> 07:09.840
Everything had been normal up to that time. We'd gone through two team
rotations. We had four teams going. We had Milt Wendler, the maroon flight

07:09.840 --> 07:19.620
director, who launched the mission. I believe Jerry actually did the
transposition and docking. I had the lunar orbit insertion. I was going to do

07:19.620 --> 07:32.500
the lunar ascent. And Glynn Lunney was really the guy who was sort of making sure
that us rookies in the non-trajectory business did our work properly and by the

07:32.500 --> 07:41.420
book. So, we had gone through the two team successions and everything was ops
normal up to that point. Jerry, why don't you say? Yeah, I'd like to pick up on

07:41.420 --> 07:51.780
a couple of and amplify a couple of James remarks. I think at the time, well I
know at the time in my own case, in Apollo 13, I was 35. five, I probably had

07:51.780 --> 08:04.200
more responsibility at age 34, 35, 36, than I've ever had before or since. And
as Gene said, this was really important in Apollo 13, because when we did get

08:04.200 --> 08:15.140
into trouble, the senior management of the agency and the senior management of
the center really only had one question of us on the flight control team is what

08:15.140 --> 08:23.820
can we do to help you? They really did leave the decision-making a bunch of
young people. I think Gene was probably 37. And he was probably the oldest

08:23.820 --> 08:34.960
flight director on that flight. I think John Aaron was 27 or something like that.
Jerry was 28. No, you weren't.

08:40.120 --> 08:49.740
Anyway, it was a young person's game. And then sometime when I reflect, and
obviously in this session we'll get into more of the problem and how we fixed it

08:49.740 --> 08:58.620
and that sort of thing. But one of the things I thought about after the flight
was over, and this didn't occur to me during the mission, as soon as we landed

08:58.620 --> 09:06.360
every one of these lunar missions, we didn't have much time to dwell on it. We
had to go on to the next one. Well, that was no exception in this case. The only

09:06.360 --> 09:18.080
difference is we'd had this big problem. And the amazing thing to me is that
after we landed, this was in April 1970, we had a complete accident

09:18.080 --> 09:31.900
investigation. We had a set of congressional hearings. We had to go fix the
problem, redo the command module pretty extensively in the oxygen system, and we

09:31.900 --> 09:40.380
went back to the moon in less than a year. In fact, we were there and about ten
months later we flew Apollo 14. Now that shows you another difference in

09:40.380 --> 09:51.820
attitude that existed 25 years ago, is when you had a problem and you had this
to have this adversity to overcome, rather than wailing and gnashing of teeth

09:51.820 --> 10:02.200
and worrying about the future, you set the problem right and charged it on
because you had not changed your initial goals. And I think that was a very

10:02.200 --> 10:15.900
fortunate time, with today's oversight and other kinds of problems that you get
into, it would be extremely difficult well, to do what we did in 1970-71, to get

10:15.900 --> 10:26.700
the program back on track. So I think it's a very interesting historical
perspective. And it's one we probably ought to keep in mind for the future.

10:28.000 --> 10:34.900
Finally, and I'm not going to say too much about it. Jerry Bostick ought to say
something about the Apollo. They've asked us to talk a little bit about the

10:34.900 --> 10:44.540
Apollo 13 movie. It was a great experience. Jerry and I got to work on it as
technical advisors. and it was an interesting way that project got started, but

10:44.540 --> 10:54.220
maybe Jerry will fill you in on that. And I really do think it's brought alive a
lot of interest in the American public. It's taken us back 25 years and it's

10:54.220 --> 11:03.020
brought up some of these successes and overcoming of failures that I think is a
very positive thing and it's good for the space program. Jerry.

11:09.660 --> 11:12.480
I had forgotten how much older you guys were.

11:16.180 --> 11:21.480
The movie has brought a lot of attention back

11:21.480 --> 11:31.960
to the mission, and it has caused all of us to reflect a lot on what happened 25
years ago. It was kind of strange to me at first that almost everyone asked the

11:31.960 --> 11:39.980
same question, Weren't you guys scared to death when the accident happened?
Weren't you running around wringing your hands and pulling your hair out?

11:42.840 --> 11:52.920
And of course, the answer was no. And then the next question is why? Well, the
only reason I can think why is because of the training that we had had, which

11:52.920 --> 12:02.260
was, I don't think we fully understood it at the time. But it's good training
for any endeavor that you undertake, and that is to try to anticipate the

12:02.260 --> 12:10.440
problems that are going to happen, have a plan of action for anything that you
can dream of that will possibly come up.

12:13.160 --> 12:26.800
But, in reality, after the accident occurred, into the next four days while we
tried to figure out collectively how to get the crew home, we didn't have a lot

12:26.800 --> 12:39.500
of time to worry about anything except the task at hand. And there was a time to
wring her hands and pull her hair. It was a great

12:39.500 --> 12:55.760
example of teamwork over the past 10 years or so, anyway. In the aerospace
industry, there's been a lot of attention on total quality management and things

12:55.760 --> 13:04.780
like that. that and it occurred to me not too long ago that even though we
didn't know it at the time, that's what we were all practicing here at the

13:04.780 --> 13:19.200
Johnson Space Center 25 and 30 years ago. It was true teamwork. Everybody knew
the task that they had to do and we tried to do the best that we could. John?

13:27.160 --> 13:35.280
Maybe I could present a little bit of what my role was in this mission and give
you my impressions of what was accomplished. I was a systems engineer, I manned

13:35.280 --> 13:43.880
one of the controller consoles in the Mission Control Center as Gene said. My
job was, since there was two spaceships involved going to the moon, one to be

13:43.880 --> 13:50.780
the mothership to transport the landing craft to the moon called the lunar
module, I was in charge of all the subsystems, all the vital systems and

13:50.780 --> 14:01.300
utilities that kept both the mothership alive and sustain the crew, so I had a
very important responsibility. My role in the mission was initially to be on the

14:01.300 --> 14:10.260
launch phase team, as Gene mentioned, and that would rotate me to be in the
landing phase. I wound up being on a part of the team that was charged with the

14:10.260 --> 14:18.880
awful decision of trying to decide whether or not to shut the mother ship down
as a result of this explosion, how much longer should we spend our precious

14:18.880 --> 14:28.620
power diagnosing this system versus a decision to shut it down and depends
really on the lifeboat. Having been a part of that decision process, we then,

14:28.760 --> 14:38.420
while the lifeboat team tried to understand how to get the mother ship back in
the vicinity of the Earth safely, I was charged with the awful responsibility of

14:38.420 --> 14:46.000
leading a team that says, given that the lifeboat team can get us back in the
vicinity of the Earth, is there any way to turn this thing back on, given this

14:46.000 --> 14:53.540
limited power that we've got? The reason I bring you through that sequence is
not only acquaintance you with kind of what my responsibility was but I think

14:53.540 --> 15:06.160
the thing that that I'm most left with that mission is as I sum it up to people
my conclusion is it works. Now what I mean by that is any complex endeavor like

15:06.160 --> 15:15.460
going to the moon which that was a very complex endeavor. We on the ground here
as part of design team you know we did design, design, design, and we did train,

15:15.560 --> 15:27.280
train, train and what if planning, try to cover every contingency, we train day
and night. I think what this mission serves as is a model that there is a method

15:27.280 --> 15:36.800
by which you not only can train and design for all the cases you think will
happen to you, but that very method and model and training process will help you

15:36.800 --> 15:46.260
react in a very successful way to things you never envisioned and never thought
you could handle. We wound up with a situation that we never trained for. The

15:46.260 --> 15:55.520
spacecraft, the mission was certainly never designed for. But those fundamental
methods in this management team and this process served to be the thing that got

15:55.520 --> 16:04.300
us home. I think that's a model for our future that says complex endeavors.
There is a method to handle the things you don't really train for, but the

16:04.300 --> 16:19.480
things you don't. As usual, John is being extremely modest about his role in the
mission. He headed a team after the accident that had to try to figure out and

16:19.480 --> 16:27.440
did how that we could get the spacecraft back with the consumables that we had
on board. We didn't have enough water. We didn't have enough electricity. We

16:27.440 --> 16:28.420
didn't have enough oxygen.

16:32.160 --> 16:45.640
And being a guy who worried about how to get the people home from an in-flight
trajectory standpoint, if I wanted to burn the engine or turn the platform on or

16:45.640 --> 16:56.480
anything to use the guidance system, I have to go to John to try to convince him
that I needed 5 amp hours. I need to do one amp. That's not it. One amp! For ten

16:56.480 --> 16:56.860
minutes.

17:01.150 --> 17:10.600
Actually, at the time... We were at 55 hours into the mission. We were at our
second rotation of the flight control team, and it takes a while to get into the

17:10.600 --> 17:20.940
groove. We always look towards that translunar phase as sort of a way to come up
to speed in all of our homework doing the final tag-ups with the various flight

17:20.940 --> 17:32.480
controllers we got and just get ourselves ready for the events that would occur
once we went into lunar orbit. We had finished the TV show, secured the downlink

17:32.480 --> 17:40.840
and one of the things the flight controllers always pride themselves in is
getting the crew to sleep on time and not having to wake them up during the

17:40.840 --> 17:53.060
sleep period. We were in the process of doing this when we asked the crew to go
through a cryo-stir And we did this because the cryogenics tended to stratify in

17:53.060 --> 18:03.640
the tank, and we always liked to get our best measurement gauging on the
cryotankage during the crew's sleep period because we knew pretty much what

18:03.640 --> 18:14.320
their metabolic use was, so we could get a good handle on our consumables. So we
told the crew to stir the cryos, and Jack Swigert reached over, and he flipped

18:14.320 --> 18:25.840
four switches. Down on the ground within just the next three seconds, three
controllers reported a problem. First one was the guidance officer who

18:25.840 --> 18:36.720
identified that we had a hardware restart. ENCO came in and said, ENCO is the
communications officer, that we had switched from narrow to wide beam and

18:36.720 --> 18:50.280
simultaneously with that we got a call from the E-com's position that we had a
main B-undervolt and about that time... Hey, excuse me, Jack Swigert first, and

18:50.280 --> 18:57.600
then a level second came down and said, Houston, we've got a problem. And it was
funny how your mind works because the first thing I thought, which one's he

18:57.600 --> 19:06.100
talking about? Is he talking about the hardware restart, the main P under fault,
or the communications problem. And that wiped clear in just a second. And then

19:06.100 --> 19:13.960
you started listening up to the loops, and all the controllers started to come
on loops, because virtually everybody in the control center had some â€” were

19:13.960 --> 19:22.460
seeing some symptoms of the problems that occurred. And it was really confusing
for those first two, three, to four minutes, because the reports kept coming in.

19:22.540 --> 19:31.000
Nothing made sense. The crew was changing the configuration on board the
spacecraft, so about the time we'd get ready to make some recommendation to

19:31.000 --> 19:42.460
them, that recommendation would change because they had changed something else.
Ah, the GNNC or the guidance and control guy was worried because he was seeing a

19:42.460 --> 19:53.240
lot of pressure decay on the quads, the RCS jets that we use for attitude
control. And this is because we didn't know it was at that time an explosion.

19:53.460 --> 20:01.800
But a shock had gone through the spacecraft that it closed a lot of the valves.
Actually, we were just bringing the propellant and the manifold to the jets and

20:01.800 --> 20:11.060
the manifold pressures were decaying. the spacecraft was incapable of being
controlled. It was a very difficult three or four minutes. But then after about

20:11.060 --> 20:19.540
three to three and a half minutes, the basic discipline and the training of the
team and the quality the controllers started to take over. In particular, the

20:19.540 --> 20:29.340
control guy recognized that the jets had been, the valves had been closed and
that's why we couldn't control attitude. So we've now started to that solve our

20:29.340 --> 20:39.380
attitude problem. The communications guy came up and said to say, until we get
our attitude problem nailed down let's use the Omni antenna. So now we were

20:39.380 --> 20:48.600
getting information constantly into the spacecraft. The guidance officer by this
time very quickly had come up and said he had the time of the hardware restart

20:48.600 --> 21:00.760
so now we could start tracing back in our data at the possible time this
occurred. So the control team, over the next 10 to 15 minutes continued to work

21:00.760 --> 21:11.820
their problems with one exception and that was the the Ecom Cae Liebergat who
had the consistent problems associated with the fuel cells and the cryogenics

21:11.820 --> 21:21.820
and it became obvious we were chasing the instrumentation problems early but by
the time we were about 10 to 15 minutes into this episode it became obvious that

21:21.820 --> 21:31.720
we were seeing some real problems but but we were still dubious about what
information we could truly believe. But the crew, the controllers, the entire

21:31.720 --> 21:39.680
team was coming to the conclusion that we had problems in fuel cells, problems
in cryos, and it looked like at least two fuel cells were done. And about this

21:39.680 --> 21:52.100
time, about fifteen minutes into this entire episode, we were in the process of
a changing shift. Glynn Lunney had come in and turned to Glynn and told him to get

21:52.100 --> 21:55.280
a hold of Chris, that he had better get in because we're in deep, serious
trouble.

21:58.540 --> 22:07.360
And it was just frustrating to see the lifeblood and the fuel cells and
cryoscaping and not being able to do anything about it. And then Jim Lovell came

22:07.360 --> 22:16.340
down and said, we're venting something. And as soon as he said venting, that
then synced, I think, everybody in the team. I think everybody sort of sent a

22:16.340 --> 22:25.760
chill down your spine. that says, my God, we had some type of an explosion, and
in my mind, the first thought I had was survival, that we're now in a survival

22:25.760 --> 22:34.500
situation, and these guys up here, somewhere along the line, in their careers,
flight controllers, have looked at this thing we call the doomsday scenario, and

22:34.500 --> 22:43.920
you look it straight in the face, and it sort of gets your attention. Go ahead.
Interestingly enough, because Gene and I have talked about this, when the

22:43.920 --> 22:54.800
accident first happened, And our thought was, now what do we got to do to go
ahead with this landing mission? Yeah. And I know you got to that survival mode

22:54.800 --> 23:02.380
in a couple of steps, because that was the way we were trained. When it happens,
what do we have to do now to make sure we can still land OK? And Jim Lovell was

23:02.380 --> 23:09.620
thinking the same way. He said, yeah, we've had some kind of problem, but we'll
get this fixed and go on and land on the moon. It's interesting how you kind of

23:09.620 --> 23:19.280
step down and all of a sudden you say, there's no more options left. Now the
game is to get them back and forget the mission of going to the moon or- We

23:19.280 --> 23:27.460
never trained this doomsday scenario because it's non-beneficial. I mean, you
end up killing the crew and the controllers end up going home. So you never

23:27.460 --> 23:37.740
train to this. So all of the training that we have, there's always some way out.
And that's the way we're trained. And it went through my mind, in fact, in the

23:37.740 --> 23:44.740
voice loops. Let's not do anything that's going to blow the mission. I was still
thinking, well, if we can't land on the Moon, we're going to go into orbit

23:44.740 --> 23:54.560
around the Moon, kind of thing. So it's, the training process is, it's
interesting how your mind down modes under this kind of situation. We continued

23:54.560 --> 24:03.820
to work on this thing for the best part of another hour. We recognized very
quickly, and we had two things going for us. In Apollo 9 mission, we had built

24:03.820 --> 24:14.620
something we call the lifeboat procedures. procedures and about 45 minutes into
this crisis we went and proceeded to start digging out these lifeboat procedures

24:14.620 --> 24:24.200
because once you do something like that you always save it. The other thing that
was useful on this mission was we had done a lot of maneuvers using the LM

24:24.200 --> 24:33.340
spacecraft during Apollo 9 and all that data was in archive, so we really
started going two directions. One got to get the data out of archives from the

24:33.340 --> 24:39.760
Apollo 9 mission and the rest of controllers to dig out their lifeboat
procedures. So I think that's all. I'll let these guys continue for a while.

24:39.980 --> 24:49.800
Yeah. Interesting. And I just, I don't know what made me think of this, but
it'll show you a little bit how, by the time we got to Apollo 13, how we were

24:49.800 --> 24:58.900
thinking about going to the moon. This was our third landing mission. We had
been there twice before on 10 and 8 and did not, Apollo 10 and Apollo 8, and did

24:58.900 --> 25:11.820
not land. So this was not a brand new experience. And I recall I had, in fact,
Gene relieved me. I was the off-going flight director with my team. And I was

25:11.820 --> 25:19.540
off playing a softball. I went down to South Houston here somewhere and was
playing a softball game with some of the other flight controllers. And we

25:19.540 --> 25:27.400
finished the game, and I went back to one of the fellows' apartments to get a
cool one, and we got a call that there had been a problem, and that we'd better

25:27.400 --> 25:38.580
get back out to the center. The first time I walked back into the control
center, I had on my sweatsuit still from baseball or playing softball. It then

25:38.580 --> 25:46.540
became very apparent I lived in Nassau Bay at that point right across the street
here. I got home very fast to get some sleep because I knew I was going to have

25:46.540 --> 25:48.080
to rotate back in the next morning.

25:50.820 --> 26:02.920
Let me draw a slight parallel here with the movie that I'm sure many of you have
seen. Actually, my take, and I got there probably 30 to 45 minutes after the

26:02.920 --> 26:12.060
accident happened, when I walked in things were as calm, it looked just like a
routine simulation that maybe a training simulation or something. There were a

26:12.060 --> 26:21.660
few more people in the room because people had come back to see what was going
on and what was happening. But I'll never be I never will forget that first look

26:21.660 --> 26:30.660
at the thing. It was it was a very calm room. People were going about their
business. Gene and Glynn Lunney were at the flight director console talking

26:30.660 --> 26:40.760
things over. And if there was a stillness and a calmness, it was kind of eerie.
The movie probably overplayed a little bit. And they had to do that. In fact,

26:41.220 --> 26:50.960
Ron Howard told Jerry and me both that there's going to be times in this movie
where I have to make it a little more emotional to make it entertaining. Because

26:50.960 --> 27:00.680
it's not a documentary. It had to be an entertaining movie. So he took a little
poetic license or dramatic license in a couple of places. But let me say this

